-- 	('2011-09-12T00:00:00+00:00','Drought','Senegal','Sahel Crisis: 2011-2017','A combination of factors including, the 2011 drought, high food prices, low agricultural production, as well as the inability of affected households to recover from the 2010 food and nutrition crisis, exacerbated the sub-region’s vulnerability in 2012. Moreover, the 2010-2011 crises in Cote d’Ivoire and Libya also contributed to increasing the vulnerability of hundreds of thousands of households that were deprived of the remittances of migrant workers who had fled these conflicts. Their return has also placed additional strain on their communities of return, notably in Chad, Niger and Mali. In 2012, approximately 18.7 million people were estimated to be food insecure and over one million children were at risk of dying from severe acute malnutrition. ([OCHA, 17 Dec 2012](https://reliefweb.int/node/551990))\r\n\r\nIn 2012, and for the third time in ten years, the Sahel region was hit by a major drought which further weakened vulnerable communities. The scale of the resulting food and nutrition crisis required all actors to join forces to save the lives of the 24 million people affected. A [three-year regional plan](https://reliefweb.int/node/634433) was developed in 2013 aiming to deliver coordinated and integrated life-saving assistance to people affected by emergencies while shaping the response to chronic needs in nine countries: Burkina Faso, Cameroon, Chad, Mali, Mauritania, Niger, Nigeria, Senegal and The Gambia. ([OCHA, 30 Aug 2017](https://reliefweb.int/node/2194999))\r\n\r\n**Lake Chad Basin**: The scale of suffering remains huge and is expected to grow: around 11 million people will require assistance in 2017. Humanitarian partners have requested US$1.5 billion to provide aid to 8.2 million people. While the response strategy focuses us on providing emergency, life-saving assistance, humanitarian actors are also calling for a collaborative approach to help address the deeper causes of the Lake Chad Basin crisis that include abject poverty, the impact of climate change, rapid population growth and under-investment in social services. At the Oslo conference on 24 Feb 2017, 14 donors pledged $458 million for relief in 2017 and an additional $214 million was announced for 2018 and beyond. ([OCHA, 24 Feb 2017](https://reliefweb.int/node/1917023))\r\n\r\n**Mali**: Needs remain high with more than 3.5 million people being food insecure and some 852,000 people in need of nutrition assistance. More than 37,000 people remain internally displaced. The majority of those in need of assistance are in Mali’s northern region.\r\nIn April 2017, the Humanitarian Response Plan for 2017 for $293 million was only 11.6% funded. OCHA warned of destabilizing consequences, as the humanitarian situation is quickly deteriorating as a direct result of the conflict. ([OCHA, 28 Apr 2017](https://reliefweb.int/node/2008544))\r\n### Appeals & Response Plans\r\n\r\n- [![OCHA: 2017 Sahel - Overview of humanitarian needs and requirements - Cover preview](https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/styles/attachment-small/public/resources-pdf-previews/689774-HNRO_Sahel-2017-EN.png) OCHA: 2017 Sahel - Overview of humanitarian needs and requirements](https://reliefweb.int/node/1811404)\r\n- [![OCHA: Sahel 2017 - Aperçu des besoins humanitaires et des fonds requis pour la réponse - Cover preview](https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/styles/attachment-small/public/resources-pdf-previews/689789-HNRO_Sahel-2017%20-%20FR.png) OCHA: Sahel 2017 - Aperçu des besoins humanitaires et des fonds requis pour la réponse](https://reliefweb.int/node/1811424)\r\n- [![OCHA: Sahel 2016 | Rapport de suivi périodique (Octobre-Décembre 2016) - Cover preview](https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/styles/attachment-small/public/resources-pdf-previews/754044-2016_pmr_final_14042017_Final-small.png) OCHA: Sahel 2016 | Rapport de suivi périodique (Octobre-Décembre 2016)](https://reliefweb.int/node/1987794)\r\n- [![OCHA: Sahel: 2014 - 2016 Regional Humanitarian Response Strategy Reviewed - Cover preview](https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/styles/attachment-small/public/resources-pdf-previews/934899-Sahel-EYReport-2016-LowRes.png) OCHA: Sahel: 2014 - 2016 Regional Humanitarian Response Strategy Reviewed](https://reliefweb.int/node/2194999)\r\n\r\n### Useful Links\r\n\r\n- [![Humanitarian Response - Logo](https://www.humanitarianresponse.info/sites/all/themes/humanitarianresponse/logo.png)](https://wca.humanitarianresponse.info)\r\n- [UNHCR Opération Sahel Portail de partage de l\'Information](http://data.unhcr.org/MaliSituation/regional.php)\r\n- [OCHA Sahel Crisis](http://www.unocha.org/sahel)\r\n- [Comité permanent Inter-Etats de Lutte contre la Sécheresse dans le Sahel](http://www.cilss.bf)\r\n- [ORS (Online Reporting System)](http://ors.ocharowca.info)\r\n- [Sahel Food Crisis platform](http://sahelresponse.org)\r\n- [![Financial Tracking Service - Logo](https://fts.unocha.org/sites/all/themes/custom/fts_public/logo.png)](https://fts.unocha.org/appeals/497/summary)','past'),
-- 	('2011-09-12T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Viet Nam','Viet Nam: Floods - Sep 2011','Between late September and early December 2011, the Mekong Delta region of Viet Nam experienced its worst flooding in 11 years, affecting over 600,000 people in the provinces of An Giang, Dong Thap, Long An, Can Tho, Vinh Long, Hau Giang and Kien Giang. Unlike the floods Viet Nam faces every year, these floods have been slow onset, with water covering large areas, paralysing the everyday life of affected communities and threatening their livelihoods. 85 people were killed; almost 13,000 families were evacuated due to flooding and landslides. Damage to property and livelihood was widespread and as much as 11,768 acres of rice paddies were lost. Six months on, some households made, where possible, efforts to rebuild their houses; however, many families whose houses had totally collapsed were still living in temporary shelters nearby their destroyed houses or continued to live in their bamboo houses with poor conditions. ([IFRC, 24 Jul 2012](https://reliefweb.int/node/512828))\r\n### Useful Links\r\n\r\n- [Central Committee for Flood and Storm Control (CCFSC)](http://www.ccfsc.gov.vn/KW367A21/Trang-chu.aspx)\r\n- [Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment - Hydro-meteorology](http://www.monre.gov.vn/v35/default.aspx?tabid=677&cateid=59)\r\n- [National Centre for Hydro-Meteorological Forecasting](http://www.nchmf.gov.vn/web/en-US/43/Default.aspx)\r\n- [Viet Nam Red Cross Society](http://chuthapdo.org.vn/redcross/en/home/index.jsp)\r\n- [Mekong River Commission: Weekly Flood Situation Report 2011](http://ffw.mrcmekong.org/weekly_report/2011/weeklyreport2011.htm)','past'),
-- 	('2011-09-01T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Colombia','Colombia: Floods and Landslides - Sep 2011','Since the start of the second rainy season in September, more than 914,280 people have been affected by floods and landslides in most of the country. Some departments, including Cesar, Chocó, Córdoba and North of Santander, are also particularly affected by the armed conflict ([OCHA, 29 Dec 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/467806)).\r\n### Useful Links\r\n\r\n- [Sistema Nacional para la Prevención y Atención de Desastres (SINPAD)](http://www.sigpad.gov.co/sigpad/index.aspx)\r\n- [Cruz Roja Colombiana](http://www.cruzrojacolombiana.org/index.php)\r\n- [Información sobre afectación por desastres naturales en Colombia en tiempo real](http://inundaciones.colombiassh.org)\r\n- [RT Video on floods](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4-C5cTb1ipI)','past'),
-- 	('2011-09-01T00:00:00+00:00','Flash Flood','South Sudan','South Sudan: Flash Floods - Sep 2011','After heavy rains triggered flash floods in and around Agok early September 2011, thousands of households were affected, a significant number of whom were displaced from the Abyei crisis ([OCHA South Sudan Weekly Humanitarian Bulletin, 8 Sep 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/445925)). An inter-agency assessment undertaken in Fangak County in Jonglei State from 10-14 November to assess the impact of flooding in August and September found that 30,000 people were directly affected by the floods and some 13,000 were displaced.([OCHA South Sudan Weekly Humanitarian Bulletin, 17 November 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/461159)).','past'),
-- 	('2011-09-01T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Mexico','Mexico: Floods - Sep 2011','Heavy rains have left at least 74 deaths and more than 40,000 people affected in the states of Chiapas, Estado de México, Guerrero, Oaxaca, Sinaloa, Tabasco y Veracruz ([Government, 6 Sep 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/445345)).','past'),
-- 	('2011-09-01T00:00:00+00:00','Storm Surge','Honduras','Honduras: Storm Surge - Sep 2011','More 400 than houses have been damaged by high tides on the Pacific Coast. Around 155 families were taken to shelters ([Govt of Honduras, 2 Sep 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/444691)).','past'),
-- 	('2011-08-27T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Russian Federation','Russian Federation: Floods - Aug 2011','The flooding in Grozny, Russian Federation, Chechnya, occurred when heavy rains, lasting for two days non-stop, led to the bursting of the dam on the river Sunzha that normally protects the city from floodwaters. The flood situation worsened on the Sunzha River in the Oktyabrsky district of Grozny, and the dam broke on 27 Aug 2011. ([IFRC bulletin, 2 Sep 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/444519))','past'),
