-- 	('2011-08-20T00:00:00+00:00','Tropical Cyclone','Nicaragua','Tropical Storm Harvey - Aug 2011','After Tropical Storm Harvey made landfall in southern Belize on Aug 20, flash floods were reported in low-lying areas and some houses were damaged or destroyed ([CDEMA, 20 Aug 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/442120)).','past'),
-- 	('2011-08-17T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Niger','Niger: Floods - Aug 2011','In August 2011, more than 13,000 people were affected by floods in the regions of Tillabéry, Zinder, Tahoua and Agadez. Five people died, nearly 1,000 houses were destroyed and crop fields were damaged ([OCHA, 1 Sep 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/444406))','past'),
-- 	('2011-08-16T00:00:00+00:00','Flash Flood','Kenya','Kenya: Floods - Aug 2011','Starting August 2011, heavy rains in northwestern Kenya caused several cases of flash flooding in the Kisumu East, Nyando, and Turkana districts. Around Kakuma, an estimated 60,000 people experienced flooding with water sources, latrines and homes damaged ([UNICEF, 17 Aug 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/442056)). As of 12 December ,Kenya Red Cross Society (KRCS) estimated at least 25 people had lost their lives in flood-related incidents and approximately 15,045 households (91,692 people) were displaced from their homes ([IFRC, 12 Dec 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/464429)).\r\n### Useful Links\r\n\r\n- [Kenya Meteorological Department](http://www.meteo.go.ke)\r\n- [FEWSNET: Kenya](http://www.fews.net/pages/country.aspx?gb=ke&l=en)','past'),
-- 	('2011-08-12T00:00:00+00:00','Flash Flood','Ethiopia','Ethiopia: Floods - Aug 2011','In Aug 2011 floods have been reported in Amhara, Tigray, Somali and Afar regions ([Government Early Warning Bulletin, 31 Aug 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/444357)).  \r\n\r\nAccording to FewsNet, about 650 households have been displaced, mainly in Amhara and Gambela and about 20 causalities were reported in Kalu (South Wollo) and Antsokia (North Shewa) ([Food Security Outlook Update, 25 Aug 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/444114)).\r\n### Useful Links\r\n\r\n- [National Meteorological Agency](http://www.ethiomet.gov.et)\r\n- [FEWSNET: Ethiopia](http://www.fews.net/pages/country.aspx?gb=et&l=en)','past'),
-- 	('2011-08-12T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Uganda','Uganda: Floods and Mudslides - Aug 2011','Mudslides caused by heavy rains left over 6,400 people in need of urgent re-settlement, 5 injured and 3 bodies still trapped under debris.  WFP distributed food aid to 26 families with the assistance of the Red Cross. [(Uganda Red Cross, 12 Aug 2011)](https://reliefweb.int/node/440761)\r\n\r\nFloods caused by heavy rains in the east have destroyed food crops. ([Uganda Red Cross, 24 Aug 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/442748))\r\n\r\nMonitoring and evaluation:\r\n1. NFIs had distribution logs which had beneficiary signatures and local leaders’ endorsement.\r\n2. Random field visits by partner’s representatives (local government and district disaster committee\r\nmembers), URCS board members and senior management to the intervention areas that included\r\nbrief beneficiary interviews for feedback.\r\n3. Regular meetings and sharing of distribution information with the district disaster management\r\ncommittee.\r\n\r\nInstitutional achievements:\r\nNational Society Capacity Building: Throughout the emergency response, URCS has been able to\r\nstrengthen several aspects of the institutions capacity:\r\n1. The National Society has increased its visibility and image as the communities, attested to by the\r\ngovernment’s and other organizations’ regular requests to have dialogue and joint activities and\r\neven taking the lead in the operation.\r\n2. Lessons are being learned on the multiple levels of interaction with government authorities, both at\r\nnational and branch/district levels.\r\n3. The administrative and operative aspects of the National Society have been strengthened with this\r\noperation, with new skills building on previous experiences. ([IFRC Final Report, 20 Mar 2012](https://reliefweb.int/node/484022))','past'),
-- 	('2011-08-08T00:00:00+00:00','Severe Local Storm','Paraguay','Paraguay: Severe Local Storm - Aug 2011','On 8 August 2011, a hailstorm with strong winds struck the Itapúa department affecting 1,714 families in the municipalities of Mayor Otaño and Carlos Antonio López destroying crops and rooftops ([IFRC, 26 Aug 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/443402)).','past'),
-- 	('2011-08-05T00:00:00+00:00','Flash Flood','Sudan','Sudan: Floods - Aug 2011','Since early Aug 2011, floods were reported in North Darfur ([OCHA, 25 Aug 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/443853)), South Darfur ([Radio Dabanga, 12 Aug 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/440620)), West Darfur ([Radio Dabanga, 4 Aug 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/439128)), the Blue Nile ([OCHA, 18 August 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/443281)), Khartoum State ([OCHA,11 August 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/441096)) and in Northern Kordofan ([Govt. Sudan,19 Aug 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/442169)) resulting in the destruction of hundreds of houses and affecting more 16,000 people and at least 2000 deaths.','past'),
-- 	('2011-08-03T00:00:00+00:00','Tropical Cyclone','Dominican Republic',NULL,NULL,NULL),
-- 	('2011-08-03T00:00:00+00:00','Tropical Cyclone','Haiti','Tropical Storm Emily - Aug 2011','As Tropical Storm Emily approached the Island of La Hispaniola with sustained winds of 85 km/h, the National Societies in Haiti and the Dominican Republic prepared themselves to monitor the situation and respond in a comprehensive way. Since both the Dominican Republic and Haiti are confronting a cholera outbreak, there is a general concern that the flooding produced by Tropical Storm Emily could exacerbate the situation. [(IFRC, 04 August 2011)](https://reliefweb.int/node/439134)\r\n### Useful Links\r\n\r\n- [Centre national de météorologie, Haïti](http://www.meteo-haiti.gouv.ht/index.html)\r\n- [Centro de Operaciones de Emergencia de la República Dominicana](http://www.coe.gov.do/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&id=8:boletin&Itemid=45)\r\n- [Redhum](http://www.redhum.org/emergencias.php)\r\n- [Tropical Storm Risk](http://www.tropicalstormrisk.com/tracker/dynamic/201105N.html)\r\n- [Haiti Shelter Cluster - Tropical Storm Emily](https://sites.google.com/site/shelterhaiti2010/home/tropical-storm)','past'),
-- 	('2011-08-01T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Mali','Mali: Floods - Aug 2011','Since the beginning of Aug 2011, Mali has been facing heavy rainfall that has resulted in\r\nflooding in some locations and overflows of ponds in others, claiming many victims ([IFRC, 8 Sep 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/445577)).','past'),
-- 	('2011-08-01T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Guinea','Guinea: Floods - Aug 2011','In 2011 the Republic of Guinea has been struck by a series of floods, particularly affecting the Prefectures of Labé (city centre), Siguiri, the sub-prefectures of Niandankoro, and Kéniébakoura and the urban districts of Mandiana (Kiniéran), Gaoual, Matam (Heremakonon) and Matoto (Yimbaya market).  \r\nThe floods have caused significant material damage and affected 2,645 families, or 16,143 persons, including more than 4,000 left homeless ([IFRC, 7 Sep 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/445543)).','past'),
-- 	('2011-08-01T00:00:00+00:00','Epidemic','Burundi','Burundi: Cholera Outbreak - Aug 2011','Since the beginning of August 2011, a cholera outbreak affected six provinces in Burundi. In general, cholera is endemic in Burundi, but because of the early start of the rainy season, the cholera cases increased. The situation became complicated in the affected districts cumulative number of cholera cases stood at 423, with nine new cases and two deaths. On 13 Aug, the ministry of health issued a disaster declaration. The Burundi Red Cross distributed hygiene kits and water and conducted community hygiene sessions and disinfection visits. By the end of the operation, the Ministry of Health declared an end to the epidemic, with no more cholera cases reported. ([IFRC, 21 Mar 2012](https://reliefweb.int/node/484554))','past'),
-- 	('2011-08-01T00:00:00+00:00','Flash Flood','Senegal','Senegal: Floods - Aug 2011','Since 1 August 2011, the western central regions of Senegal have been experiencing torrential rains. Some 5,214 people have been affected by the floods in Thies. Additional rains caused flash floods, increasing the vulnerability of the community. [(IFRC, 11 August 2011)](https://reliefweb.int/node/440312)','past'),
