-- 	('2014-03-23T00:00:00+00:00','Epidemic','Togo','West Africa: Ebola Outbreak - Mar 2014','- In March 2014, a rapidly evolving outbreak of Ebola haemorrhagic fever [started](https://reliefweb.int/node/646821) in Guinea. The outbreak subsequently spread to [Liberia](https://reliefweb.int/node/648711), [Sierra Leone](https://reliefweb.int/node/662629),  [Nigeria](https://reliefweb.int/node/679655), [Senegal](https://reliefweb.int/node/687718), and [Mali](https://reliefweb.int/node/702953).\r\n- 1 Aug 2014: WHO and the government of Sierra Leone, Guinea and Liberia launched a [joint US$ 100 million response plan](https://reliefweb.int/node/680234).\r\n- 8 Aug 2014: WHO [declared](https://reliefweb.int/node/681936) the Ebola outbreak in West Africa a Public Health Emergency of International Concern (PHEIC).\r\n- 28 Aug 2014: WHO issued a \"[roadmap](https://reliefweb.int/node/686986)\" to scale up the international response.\r\n- 19 Sep 2014:  [UN Mission for Ebola Emergency Response (UNMEER)](https://reliefweb.int/node/697370) established.\r\n- 17 Oct 2014: WHO [declared](https://reliefweb.int/node/700892) Senegal free of Ebola virus transmission.\r\n- 20 Oct 2014: WHO [declared](https://reliefweb.int/node/701300) Nigeria free of Ebola virus transmission.\r\n- 19 Jan 2015: WHO [declared](https://reliefweb.int/node/808201) Mali free of Ebola virus transmission.\r\n- 21 Jan 2015: [Updated Overview of Needs and Requirements for Jan-Jun 2015](https://reliefweb.int/node/813221) launched.\r\n- 8 May 2015: WHO [declared](https://reliefweb.int/node/980576) Liberia free of Ebola virus transmission.\r\n- 31 Jul 2015: UNMEER [closed](https://reliefweb.int/node/1105791) and transitioned oversight of the UN system’s Ebola emergency response to WHO as of 1 Aug.  \r\n- 7 Nov 2015: WHO [declared](https://reliefweb.int/node/1253641) Sierra Leone free of Ebola virus transmission.\r\n- 29 Dec 2015: WHO [declared](https://reliefweb.int/node/1324111/) the end of Ebola virus transmission in the Republic of Guinea.\r\n- 14 Jan 2016: WHO [declared](https://reliefweb.int/node/1344206/) the end of the most recent outbreak of Ebola virus disease in Liberia and said all known chains of transmission have been stopped in West Africa.\r\n- 15 Jan 2016: A new case of Ebola has been [confirmed](https://reliefweb.int/node/1346201) in Sierra Leone. The country is still in a 90-day period of enhanced surveillance following the declaration on 7 November 2015 of the end of Ebola transmission in the country.\r\n- 17 Mar 2016: WHO and the government of Sierra Leone [marked](https://reliefweb.int/node/1442801) the end of the recent flare-up of Ebola virus disease in the country.\r\n- 18 Mar 2016: Guinean health officials in the region [alerted](https://reliefweb.int/node/1444581) WHO and partners on 16 March to 3 unexplained deaths in recent weeks in the village of Koropara and said other members of the same family are currently showing symptoms characteristic of Ebola.\r\n- 29 Mar 2016: WHO [said](https://reliefweb.int/node/1457526) Ebola situation in West Africa no longer constitutes a Public Health Emergency of International Concern.\r\n- 1 Jun 2016: WHO [declares](https://reliefweb.int/node/1550166) the end of Ebola virus transmission in the Republic of Guinea.\r\n- 9 Jun 2016: WHO [declares](https://reliefweb.int/node/1561866) the end of the most recent Ebola virus disease outbreak in Liberia. \r\n\r\n- [Latest WHO Ebola response roadmap - Interactive map journal](http://maps.who.int/MapJournal/?appid=7462923f64ef44cb8a1dbde6cda64906)\r\n- [UNMEER Situation Reports](https://reliefweb.int/updates?source=15405&format=10#content)\r\n### Useful Links\r\n\r\n- [WHO Ebola virus disease outbreak](http://www.who.int/csr/disease/ebola/en)\r\n- [![Humanitarian Response - Logo](https://www.humanitarianresponse.info/sites/all/themes/humanitarianresponse/logo.png)](https://www.humanitarianresponse.info/disaster/ep-2014-000041-gin)\r\n- [UN Global Ebola Response](http://ebolaresponse.un.org)\r\n- [CDC Ebola](http://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/outbreaks/guinea/index.html)\r\n- [MEDBOX Ebola Toolbox](http://www.medbox.org/ebola-toolbox/listing)\r\n- [Ebola alerts on HealthMap](http://healthmap.org/ebola)\r\n- [OpenStreetMap West Africa Ebola Response](https://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/2014_West_Africa_Ebola_Response)\r\n- [Ebola Response Anthropology Platform](http://www.ebola-anthropology.net)\r\n- [![Financial Tracking Service - Logo](https://fts.unocha.org/sites/all/themes/custom/fts_public/logo.png)](https://ftsarchive.unocha.org/pageloader.aspx?page=emerg-emergencyDetails&emergID=16506)','past'),
-- 	('2014-03-17T00:00:00+00:00','Epidemic','Fiji','Fiji: Dengue Outbreak - Mar 2014','By mid-March 2014, Fiji\'s Ministry of Health had confirmed 11 deaths and over 10,000 suspected cases in a dengue outbreak, which had started in November 2013. The Australian Government donated AUD 750,000 to the Fiji Government to purchase medical supplies and support a public health awareness campaign. The People’s Republic of China donated USD 50,000. The Government is running a campaign to remove mosquito breeding sites in Suva. ([OCHA, 17 Mar 2014](https://reliefweb.int/node/645073))\r\n\r\nBy April, there were over 20,000 suspected dengue cases and a total of 12 confirmed deaths ([WHO, 8 Apr 2014](https://reliefweb.int/node/654263)).\r\n\r\nBy the end of May, the number of new cases had decreased steeply since the week ending 31 Mar from 1,576 to 389 suspected cases in the first week of May. The cumulative figure since November 2013 stood at 25,300 suspected cases. ([Govt, 16 May 2014](https://reliefweb.int/node/661137))','past'),
-- 	('2014-03-13T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Colombia','Colombia: Floods and Landslides - Mar-Jul 2014','Colombia’s first rainy season of 2014 began in mid-March ([OCHA, 31 Apr 2014](https://reliefweb.int/node/661651)). By the end of May, a total of 41,151 people had been affected in 182 municipalities of the country, with the Centre (Caquetá), the Caribbean Coast (Magdalena) and the Pacific region (Chocó, Cauca) being the most affected. ([OCHA, 31 May 2014](https://reliefweb.int/node/667437))\r\n\r\nIn mid-June, more than 4,000 people were affected by flooding in Alto Putumayo ([OCHA, 14 Jun 2014](https://reliefweb.int/node/667505)).\r\n\r\nBy July, flooding had affected more than 16,000 in Putumayo.  Forecasts indicate that the rainfall will likely continue throughout the coming months. ([OCHA, 31 Jul 2014](https://reliefweb.int/node/683986)).','past'),
-- 	('2014-03-12T00:00:00+00:00','Drought','Pakistan','Pakistan: Drought - 2014-2017','According to authorities in Tharparkar district, Sindh province, 99 children and 67 adults (43 men and 24 women) have reportedly died in Tharparkar since the beginning of 2014 due to a combination of chronic malnutrition, a lack of access to effective health facilities, lower than average rainfall in Chachro, Diplo, Khinser, Islamkot, Mithi tehsils (sub-districts), and an outbreak of sheep pox which has killed thousands of small animals. \r\n\r\nCrop failure due to low rainfall, coupled with loss of small animals has greatly reduced the impoverished communities’ purchasing power. Poverty is endemic in the sparsely populated district with acute malnutrition rates in children as high as 20 per cent, well above the emergency threshold of 15 per cent. The outbreak of sheep pox has aggravated the situation in Tharparkar, possibly having killed thousands of small animals, critical to household food security. ([OCHA, 20 March 2014](https://reliefweb.int/node/646370))\r\n\r\nMore than 190 children have died and 22,000 have been hospitalised in Tharparkar district in 2016 because of drought-related waterborne and viral diseases. Tharparkar is facing severe drought for the fourth consecutive year, and access to health services is reported to be very difficult, with families travelling an average distance of 17km to reach the nearest health facility. ([Assessment Capacities Project, 16 Feb 2016](http://www.reliefweb.int/node/1396391))\r\n\r\nAccording to the Joint UN Needs Assessment, several districts have been severely affected by extreme water scarcity (62% in Jamshoro and 100% in Tharparkar), and it has resulted in reduced harvest by 34-53% and livestock by 48%. ([UNICEF, 30 Jun 2016](https://reliefweb.int/node/1595461))\r\n\r\nIn Tharparkar District and the surrounding areas of Sindh Province, a third consecutive year of cereal production shortfalls due to drought, coupled with losses of small animals, has aggravated food insecurity and caused acute malnutrition. ([FAO, 30 Nov 2016](https://reliefweb.int/node/1806214))\r\n\r\nSince 2013, Tharparkar has been affected by a drought‐like situation impacting livelihoods, nutrition and health conditions. The total under‐ 5 deaths were reported at 234 in 2013, 326 in 2014, and 398 in 2015, rising from 173 in 2011 and 188 in 2012. According to media reports, the incidence of under‐five deaths in Tharparkar is still on rise during the first half of 2016 with 243 deaths recorded. This may suggest a worsening health and nutrition situation following the start of the drought period. ([WFP, 19 Sep 2016](https://reliefweb.int/node/1713536))\r\n\r\nAt least nine more infants died due to malnutrition and the outbreak of various diseases in arid Tharparkar district over a two-day period in December, raising the toll to 476 for 2016, according to local media. ([Alhasan Systems, 01 Jan 2017](https://reliefweb.int/node/1844084))\r\n\r\nA joint UN observation mission took place in drought-hit Tharparkar, Umerkot and Sanghar districts from 13-17 February, 2017. The resulting mission report stated that the areas remain vulnerable and that the situation may become critical or deteriorate into a \'humanitarian emergency\' if little or no rain falls during the coming monsoon, and if immediate needs are not met. The mission found that the vulnerabilities outlined in an [August 2016 needs assessment](https://reliefweb.int/node/1670556/) remain, while recommendations from detailed assessments and missions conducted from 2015-2016 have not been put into practice. ([UNCT, 17 Feb 2017](https://reliefweb.int/node/1939704))\r\n\r\nIn the districts of Tharparkar, Umerkot and Sanghar in southeastern Sindh Province, below-average rains throughout 2016 sharply reduced the 2016/17 cereal production. This, coupled with losses of small animals due to diseases and severe shortages of fodder and water, has aggravated food insecurity and caused acute malnutrition. ([FAO, 09 May 2017](https://reliefweb.int/node/2024489))\r\n\r\nForecast models indicate that there is a 50 to 60 per cent probability of an El Niño event developing in the second half of 2017, with Pakistan categorized as a high-risk country. Worsening drought conditions could potentially affect an estimated 300,000 of the most vulnerable people — including 192,680 children — in Sindh province. There will also be an increased chance of severe monsoon rains in the north. Humanitarian partners are developing a preparedness plan aligned with priorities identified by the Government of Pakistan. ([OCHA, 19 Jun 2017 ](https://reliefweb.int/node/2082584/))\r\n### Useful Links\r\n\r\n- [![Humanitarian Response - Logo](https://www.humanitarianresponse.info/sites/all/themes/humanitarianresponse/logo.png)](https://pak.humanitarianresponse.info)\r\n- [OCHA Pakistan](http://www.unocha.org/pakistan)\r\n- [National Disaster Management Authority (NDMA)](http://www.ndma.gov.pk)\r\n- [Sindh Provincial Disaster Management Authority (PDMA)](http://www.pdma.gos.pk/new)','past'),
