-- 	('2010-06-26T00:00:00+00:00','Tropical Cyclone','Nicaragua','Hurricane Alex - Jun 2010','Alex was the 1st hurricane of the 2010 hurricane season in the Atlantic Ocean. It reached category 2 and it was born in the Caribbean Sea moving slowly to the west reaching land on the northern part of Belize City. On June 26th, it was elevated to Tropical Storm category when it touched Belize. It lost strength to Tropical Depression on June 27th but it increased strength by the time it reached the Golf of Mexico and it transformed to hurricane on June 29th, 2010. All along its trajectory it affected Honduras, Nicaraguay, Belize, Guatemala, El Salvador and Mexico. ([CEPREDENAC, 14 October 2010](https://reliefweb.int/node/371038))\r\n\r\nIn Mexico, Hurricane Alex affected 170,000 people and left almost twenty dead. The Government of Mexico declared a state of emergency for 87 municipalities in the States of Coahuila, Nuevo León, and Tamaulipas. ([OCHA, 12 July 2010](https://reliefweb.int/node/360894))','past'),
-- 	('2010-06-22T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Dominican Republic','Dominican Republic: Floods - Jun 2010','The heavy rains affecting the Dominican Republic over the past two weeks have left six people dead and 1,000 houses flooded in Santo Domingo and in several provinces of the interior of the country. Flooding caused 9,500 people to evacuate to official emergency shelters or houses of relatives and friends ([OCHA, 5 July 2010](https://reliefweb.int/report/bolivia/redlac-weekly-note-emergencies-latin-america-caribbean-year-3-issue-164)).','past'),
-- 	('2010-06-22T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Brazil','Brazil: Floods - Jun 2010','Days of heavy rain in the states of Alagoas and Pernambuco caused rivers to break their banks and burst dams, flooding towns and leaving more than 40,000 people homeless, state emergency officials said ([Reuters, 23 June 2010](https://reliefweb.int/report/brazil/rescuers-rush-aid-brazil-flood-towns-44-dead)). So far, the official death toll is 44, with 600 reported missing ([UNICEF, 30 June 2010](https://reliefweb.int/report/brazil/brazil-floods-leave-thousands-children-homeless-alagoas-and-pernambuco)).','past'),
