-- 	('2010-06-21T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Togo','West/Central Africa: Floods - Jun 2010','About a dozen people, including women and children, have been confirmed dead in Abidjan, Côte d\'Ivoire, after heavy rain storms this week caused mudslides in some of the most run-down areas of the country\'s main port.\r\n\r\n\"A number of people are missing and we have recorded significant damage, including destroyed homes,\" said Fiacre Kili, director of the Ivorian Office of Civil Protection, on 25 June. Local leaders said thousands of people had been displaced, but no official count has been conducted ([IRIN, 25 Jun 2010](https://reliefweb.int/report/c%C3%B4te-divoire/brief-dozen-die-c%C3%B4te-divoire-rains)).','past'),
-- 	('2010-06-21T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Panama','Panama: Floods - Jun 2010','From mid June to early July, heavy rains affected Panama producing floods, water surges and landslides.Consequently, the National Civil Protection System (Sistema Nacional de Protección Civil - SINAPROC) declared a state of emergency in the Tararé River basin, in the Barriada Altos Tataré (Panamá province) and in the communities of El Cacao and El Balo ([IFRC, 23 Feb 2011](https://reliefweb.int/report/panama/panama-floods-dref-operation-n%C2%B0-mdrpa006-final-report)).','past'),
-- 	('2010-06-17T00:00:00+00:00','Epidemic','Gabon','Gabon: Chikungunya and Dengue Outbreaks - May 2010','From April through July 2010, over 500 cases of Chikungunya and Dengue fever were registered in five cities in Gabon (Franceville, Lastourville, Koulamoutou, Moanda and Mounana),  putting some 50,000 people at risk .Red Cross intervention contributed to stopping the spread of the diseases. ([IFRC, 21 Feb 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/390350))','past'),
-- 	('2010-06-16T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Myanmar','Myanmar: Floods and Landslides - Jun 2010','In mid-June 2010, the Northern Rakhine State in Myanmar faced continuous rains that caused flooding in several areas, including Maungdaw and Buthidaung. By 16 June, the government confirmed the death of 42 people ([OCHA, 16 Jun 2010](http://www.reliefweb.int/node/358367)), with this number rising to 68 by 2 July. Joint needs assessments estimated that about 29,000 families were severely affected by the floods, including 634 houses completely destroyed in Buthidaung and 180 in Maungdaw ([OCHA, 2 Jul 2010](http://www.reliefweb.int/node/359914)). In response, OCHA released an Emergency Cash Grant of USD 49,500 for the purchase of NFIs including tarpaulin sheets, kitchen sets and mosquito nets. ([OCHA, 28 Jun 2010](http://www.reliefweb.int/node/359380))','past'),
-- 	('2010-06-16T00:00:00+00:00','Earthquake','Indonesia','Indonesia: Papua - Sulawesi  Earthquakes - Jun 2010','A power string of six earthquakes shook the northern coast of Indonesia’s Papua province on 16 June 2010 ([CNN, 16 Jun 2010](http://www.reliefweb.int/node/358336)). Yapen Island, with a population of about 70,000 people, was severely affected with one church destroyed and at least 150 homes damaged. ([ABC, 16 Jun 2010](https://reliefweb.int/node/1818644)) The largest quake had a magnitude of 7.1 and a depth of 10km. ([OCHA, 22 Jun 2010](http://www.reliefweb.int/node/16847))  \r\n\r\nAt least seventeen people were killed, with 10,000 displaced, and 2,556 buildings were damaged or destroyed in Yapen. ([US Geological Survey, 6 Aug 2010](http://www.reliefweb.int/node/790646))','past'),
-- 	('2010-06-15T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Bangladesh','Bangladesh: Floods and Landslides - Jun 2010',NULL,'past'),
-- 	('2010-06-11T00:00:00+00:00','Epidemic','Cameroon','Cameroon: Cholera Outbreak - Jun 2010','In 2010, the Far North and North regions of Cameroon experienced the most serious cholera epidemic in Cameroon for several decades. The first case was registered on 6 May, and the disease spread rapidly, reaching all 28 health districts that make up the Far North region. In July, the cholera epidemic reached the North region and affected 10 out of the 15 health districts. The week of 12 to 17 Oct was the most dangerous one with more than 8,000 cases of cholera registered and more than 500 deaths just for the Far North region. Thanks to joint efforts by the Government and its partners, the number of cases and deaths began to drop progressively week after week as from November. By the end of the year, 9,399 cases and 599 deaths were registered in Far North region, while the North region had registered 494 cases, including 22 deaths. ([IFRC, 24 May 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/404445))','past'),
-- 	('2010-06-03T00:00:00+00:00','Mud Slide','Kyrgyzstan','Kyrgyzstan: Mudslides - Jun 2010','On 3 June 2010, heavy rainfall caused serious mudslides in southern Kyrgyzstan, affecting 8,350 people (1,670 households) in the Jalalabat and Osh regions. Houses, roads, cultivated lands and dams were destroyed or damaged. The most seriously affected villages were Akman and Suzak, with 1,205 families whose houses were damaged or destroyed.\r\n \r\nIFRC allocated funds on 9 June to deliver assistance to some 2,835 beneficiaries. ([IFRC, 09 Jun 2010](https://reliefweb.int/node/357536/)) The operation was implemented over four months and completed 7 October. ([IFRC, 07 Feb 2011](https://reliefweb.int/node/388163))','past'),
-- 	('2010-06-02T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Afghanistan','Afghanistan: Floods - Jun 2010',NULL,'past'),
-- 	('2010-06-02T00:00:00+00:00','Tropical Cyclone','India',NULL,NULL,NULL),
-- 	('2010-06-02T00:00:00+00:00','Tropical Cyclone','Oman',NULL,NULL,NULL),
-- 	('2010-06-02T00:00:00+00:00','Tropical Cyclone','Pakistan','Tropical Cyclone Phet - Jun 2010','Tropical Cyclone Phet in the Arabian Sea struck the Oman coast on 4 June 2010. The cyclone hit the areas of Thatta and Bhanbor (Sindh) in Pakistan on 6 June. The strong wind and rain killed at least 10 people, and more than 7,000 people were evacuated from different areas of the Badin district (Sindh). ([IFRC, 8 Jun 2010](https://reliefweb.int/node/357307/)) An IFRC operation was implemented from 8 to 25 June. ([IFRC, 17 Sep 2010](https://reliefweb.int/node/368330))','past'),
-- 	('2010-05-28T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Philippines','Philippines: Floods and Landslides - May 2010','In the Philippines, a flashflood occurred in Sultan Kudarat, Maguindanao on 26 May 2010 due to heavy rains. About 47,552 persons or 9,388 families were affected in Brgys Bulalo, Salimbao, Limbo, Gang, Calsada, Banubo, Katuli, Macaguiling, Mulaog and Senditan. Fifteen houses were damaged. ([Government of the Philippines, 29 May 2010](https://reliefweb.int/node/356422/))','past'),
-- 	('2010-05-28T00:00:00+00:00','Volcano','Ecuador','Ecuador: Tungurahua Volcano - May 2010','On 28 May 2010 Ecuador’s National Geophysics Institute reported hot explosive volcanic material blasted down the slopes of the Tungurahua Volcano. Currently there are 2,500 displaced persons that have taken refuge in 7 collective centres located in the surrounding areas ([IFRC 29 May 2010](https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/5024CCAAE1620911492577330001694E-Full_Report.pdf)).','past'),
-- 	('2010-05-27T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','Costa Rica',NULL,NULL,NULL),
-- 	('2010-05-27T00:00:00+00:00','Flood','El Salvador',NULL,NULL,NULL),
